properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Bitterly cold temperatures combined with light to moderate winds are will bring extreme wind chill values to a few sites in northern Qikiqtaaluk. Wind chill values near minus 50 will are expected in Clyde River and Pond Inlet tonight. These wind chill values are expected to moderate by Monday morning. As well, the gusty winds at Clyde River will bring poor visibility at times in blowing snow this evening. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An intense low pressure system will bring 10 to 20 millimetres of rain between Monday night and Tuesday evening over Southern and Central Quebec. Further north, snowfall amounts of 15 to 25 centimetres are possible from Monday morning to Tuesday evening in a corridor stretching from Abitibi towards Chaleur Bay. Snow accompanied by moderate winds may reduce visibilities locally in blowing snow. Freezing rain is likely in the vicinity of the snow-to-rain transition area. A more important episode of freezing rain is also likely for regions of the St. Lawrence Valley between Montreal and Quebec City on Tuesday. The Quebec City Area will likely be the most affected region. Travel could be difficult, especially at rush hour Tuesday morning. There is still much uncertainty about the track of this system and thus about the type and amount of precipitation expected. Please stay tuned for future forecasts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong northwest winds of 40 gusting 60 km/h combined with bitterly cold air is giving near-blizzard conditions with wind chill values near -55 this evening. The near-blizzard conditions and extreme wind chill values will slowly moderate as the winds diminish through the night. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard will end in Coral Harbour this evening as the winds subside. An intense low pressure system over Baffin Island and a strong ridge of high pressure to the west combine to give northwest winds gusting to 60 km/h and low visibilities in blowing snow this evening. The wind should ease through the night period and the blowing snow will taper off. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
